/ɑˈstiɹ/, /ɒˈstɪə(ɹ)/, /ɔˈstiɹ/, /ɔːˈstɪə(ɹ)/
<p><b>Adjective</b></p><ol><li>Grim or severe in manner or appearance.</li><li>Lacking decoration; trivial; not extravagant or gaudy.</li><li>Adhering to the economic policy of austerity.</li><li>Harsh; astringent.</li></ol><p>From Ancient Greek <i>αὐστηρός</i> (austērós, "bitter, harsh, astringent"), having the specific meaning "making the tongue dry" (originally used of fruits, wines), related to <i>αὔω</i> (aúō, "to singe"), <i>αὖος</i> (aûos, "dry").</p></html><p>IPA Extensions (U+0250–U+02AF):</p><p>ɐɑɒɓɔɕɖɗɘəɚɛɜɝɞɟɠɡɢɣɤɥɦɧɨɩɪɫɬɭɮɯɰɱɲɳɴɵɶɷɸɹɺɻɼɽɾɿʀʁʂʃʄʅʆʇʈʉʊʋʌʍʎʏʐʑʒʓʔʕʖʗʘʙʚʛʜʝʞʟʠʡʢʣʤʥʦʧʨʩʪʫʬʭʮʯ</p><p>Modifier Letters (U+02B0–U+02FF):</p><p>ʰʱʲʳʴʵʶʷʸʹʺʻʼʽʾʿˀˁ˂˃˄˅ˆˇˈˉˊˋˌˍˎˏːˑ˒˓˔˕˖˗˘˙˚˛˜˝˞˟ˠˡˢˣˤ˥˦˧˨˩˪˫ˬ˭ˮ˯˰˱˲˳˴˵˶˷˸˹˺˻˼˽˾˿</p><p>Word-wrap test. The following IPA transcription is long enough to require wrapping at 16pt:</p><p>ɐɑɒɓɔɕɖɗɘəɚɛɜɝɞɟɠɡɢɣɤɥɦɧɨɩɪɫɬɭɮɯɰɱɲɳɴɵɶɷɸɹɺɻɼɽɾɿʀʁʂʃ</p>/ˈmitɪŋ/, /ˈmiːtɪŋ/
<p><b>Noun</b></p><ol><li>(gerund,&#32;uncountable) The act of persons or things that meet.</li><li>A gathering of persons for a purpose; an assembly.</li><li>(<i>collective</i>) The people at such a gathering.</li><li>An encounter between people, even accidental.</li><li>A place or instance of junction or intersection; a confluence.</li><li>(rustic&#32;US,&#32;dated) A religious service held by a charismatic preacher in small towns in the United States.</li><li>(<i>Quakerism</i>) An administrative unit in the Religious Society of Friends (Quakers).</li></ol><p>From Middle English <i>meeting</i>, <i>meting</i>, from Old English <i>mēting</i>, <i>ġemēting</i> ("meeting, assembly, association, society"), equivalent to <i>meet</i> +&lrm; <i>-ing</i>. Cognate with West Frisian <i>moeting</i> ("meeting, encounter"), Dutch <i>ontmoeting</i> ("meeting, encounter"), Middle Low German <i>mö̂tinge</i> ("meeting"). Compare also German Low German <i>Möte</i> ("meeting, encounter"), Danish <i>møde</i> ("meeting, encounter"), Swedish <i>möte</i> ("meeting, encounter"), Icelandic <i>mót</i> ("meeting"). Related to <i>moot</i>.</p><p>From Middle English <i>metynge</i>, <i>metinde</i>, <i>metand</i>, from Old English <i>mētende</i>, <i>&#42;ġemētende</i>, from Proto-Germanic <i>&#42;mōtijandz</i>, present participle of Proto-Germanic <i>&#42;mōtijaną</i> ("to meet"), equivalent to <i>meet</i> +&lrm; <i>-ing</i>.</p></html><p>Phonetic Extensions (U+1D00–U+1D7F):</p><p>ᴀᴁᴂᴃᴄᴅᴆᴇᴈᴉᴊᴋᴌᴍᴎᴏᴐᴑᴒᴓᴔᴕᴖᴗᴘᴙᴚᴛᴜᴝᴞᴟᴠᴡᴢᴣᴤᴥᴦᴧᴨᴩᴪᴫᴬᴭᴮᴯᴰᴱᴲᴳᴴᴵᴶᴷᴸᴹᴺᴻᴼᴽᴾᴿᵀᵁᵂᵃᵄᵅᵆᵇᵈᵉᵊᵋᵌᵍᵎᵏᵐᵑᵒᵓᵔᵕᵖᵗᵘᵙᵚᵛᵜᵝᵞᵟᵠᵡᵢᵣᵤᵥᵦᵧᵨᵩᵪᵫᵬᵭᵮᵯᵰᵱᵲᵳᵴᵵᵶᵷᵸᵹᵺᵻᵼᵽᵾᵿ</p><p>Phonetic Extensions Supplement (U+1D80–U+1DBF):</p><p>ᶀᶁᶂᶃᶄᶅᶆᶇᶈᶉᶊᶋᶌᶍᶎᶏᶐᶑᶒᶓᶔᶕᶖᶗᶘᶙᶚᶛᶜᶝᶞᶟᶠᶡᶢᶣᶤᶥᶦᶧᶨᶩᶪᶫᶬᶭᶮᶯᶰᶱᶲᶳᶴᶵᶶᶷᶸᶹᶺᶻᶼᶽᶾᶿ</p><p>pronunciation /prəˌnʊnsiˈeɪʃən/ noun</p><p>The way in which a word or language is spoken. The transcription uses IPA symbols including ə (schwa), ʊ (near-close back rounded vowel), and ʃ (voiceless postalveolar fricative).</p><p>schwa /ʃwɑː/ noun</p><p>The mid-central vowel ə, the most common vowel sound in English. Appears in unstressed syllables, e.g. the first vowel in <em>about</em> [əˈbaʊt] and the vowel in <em>the</em> before consonants [ðə].</p>